HIGH|internal/repro/repro.go:75|The internal/repro package (Reproduce, Stamp, Verdict) is the only code that builds an EvidenceExec block, applies the 2-run determinism rule, and stamps verdict=confirmed/skeptic=repro onto a finding — but it has ZERO non-test importers. The verify pipeline (internal/verify/pipeline.go) wires the run_tests/run_script tools into the skeptic LLM loop via EnableExecution but never calls repro.Stamp, so in a real `atcr verify --exec` run JSONFinding.EvidenceExec is never populated. Epic SC-3 (evidence_exec populated, verdict confirmed) and SC-4 (evidence flows findings.json to report.md to gate) are not met end-to-end; the skeptic verdict in an --exec run remains a model self-report via parseVerdict — the exact hallucination risk the epic set out to eliminate.|Wire the write-back into internal/verify/pipeline.go after verifyFinding: when an --exec skeptic reproduces a finding, call repro.Reproduce/repro.Stamp on the in-memory findings[i] before findings.json is re-emitted. Add an end-to-end test (through the production pipeline with a faked backend) asserting evidence_exec appears in findings.json and the Reproduced badge in report.md after `verify --exec`. If the write-back is genuinely out of scope, delete the repro package and the report/schema plumbing so dead code does not imply a working feature.|correctness|240|internal/repro/repro.go:47-99|claude
HIGH|internal/sandbox/docker.go:163|DockerBackend.Run uses exec.CommandContext, which on timeout sends SIGKILL to the `docker run` CLI client, not to the container the daemon runs. The workload keeps consuming CPU/memory/PIDs until it exits on its own, and --rm only fires once it actually stops, so the per-run wall-clock cap and resource caps are not reclaimed on timeout — the central resource-protection guarantee fails for a script that ignores signals.|Give each run a --name or --cidfile and on timeout explicitly `docker kill` it (via cmd.Cancel or a deferred kill keyed on runCtx.Err()==DeadlineExceeded), or run with a reaper. Verify with a script that traps SIGTERM and sleeps past the timeout, then assert no container with that name survives.|correctness|120|internal/sandbox/docker.go:140-197|claude
HIGH|internal/sandbox/docker.go:167|Run points cmd.Stdout and cmd.Stderr at a single unbounded bytes.Buffer; truncation to MaxOutputBytes happens only AFTER cmd.Run() returns. The container --memory cgroup does not bound host-side pipe output, so a model-authored script that floods stdout (e.g. yes or cat /dev/zero) grows the atcr host process heap without limit and can OOM the reviewer machine — the host capture path is outside the sandbox caps.|Wrap the capture in a limited writer that stops accepting bytes once MaxOutputBytes (plus a small margin) is reached, so capture is bounded during the run rather than after. Verify with a script emitting far more than MaxOutputBytes and assert bounded host allocation plus a correct truncation marker.|performance|60|internal/sandbox/docker.go:160-174|claude
MEDIUM|internal/tools/dispatch.go:146|Tool gating for run_tests/run_script lives only in fanout.wireToolDefs (what the model is TOLD about); Dispatcher.Execute looks up d.handlers[name] with no check that the call was offered to the calling agent, and EnableExecution registers the exec handlers on the single dispatcher shared by the whole pool. The read-only guarantee for non-exec agents is therefore advisory, not structural — if any future caller enables exec non-uniformly across agents sharing one dispatcher, a non-exec agent could invoke run_script by simply naming it. No live exploit today: the sole exec caller, verify, sets exec uniformly for all skeptics.|Pass the agent's allowed tool set (or Exec flag) into Execute and reject any call whose name was not offered to this agent, or gate the exec handlers behind a per-call capability rather than a globally-registered handler. Verify with a test where a non-exec agent emits a run_script tool_call and asserts it is refused.|security|120|internal/tools/dispatch.go:146-191|claude
MEDIUM|internal/sandbox/docker.go:214|Preflight's trivial container passes only --network/--read-only/--cap-drop/--security-opt/--user and omits --memory, --cpus, --pids-limit, --tmpfs, -v and --workdir. A malformed operator cap value (e.g. cpus:abc, memory:512 without unit) therefore passes preflight and only fails at the first real run_tests call mid-review as an opaque backend fault, instead of failing fast at --exec startup as the preflight contract promises.|Build the preflight container from the same dockerRunArgs hardening (caps, tmpfs, a throwaway -v) running `true`, so a bad cap value is caught before the review starts. Verify with a config carrying an invalid cpus value and assert preflight, not the first run, fails.|error-handling|30|internal/sandbox/docker.go:202-221|claude
MEDIUM|internal/registry/sandbox.go:42|SandboxConfig.Validate checks Backend, Image, TestCommand, PidsLimit and TimeoutSecs but never inspects Memory or CPUs, which are operator strings injected verbatim into docker run --memory/--cpus. A typo like memory:512 (bytes not 512m) or cpus:0 passes config load and then either fails the container at runtime or silently weakens the cap, even though the block treats resource caps as a precondition.|In Validate, reject a non-empty Memory/CPUs that does not parse as a docker size / positive float (empty still inherits the hardened default). Verify with table tests covering 512, 0, abc, and valid 512m / 1.5.|error-handling|30|internal/registry/sandbox.go:42-66|claude
MEDIUM|internal/tools/exec_tools.go:97|runScriptHandler lets a.Timeout (model-controlled integer seconds) replace d.execTimeout with no upper clamp. SandboxConfig.TimeoutSecs is validated against MaxTimeoutSecs, but the model's per-call override is not, so a model can request a run far longer than the operator's configured and validated per-run budget (bounded only by any agent ctx deadline, which may be large). Combined with the orphaned-container timeout issue this magnifies resource exposure.|Clamp a.Timeout to the configured max (carry the max onto the dispatcher alongside execTimeout) and floor non-positive values. Verify with a run_script call requesting an oversized timeout and assert the effective deadline is capped.|security|15|internal/tools/exec_tools.go:89-102|claude
MEDIUM|internal/report/render.go:181|writeReproducedBlock emits the green Reproduced badge whenever f.EvidenceExec != nil with no verdict check, but repro.Stamp attaches EvidenceExec unconditionally — including the Verdict cases that return unverifiable (timeout, disagreeing exit codes, or both-zero deterministic PASS). A finding that explicitly did NOT reproduce (e.g. both runs exit 0) would render Reproduced: cmd (exit 0), lying to the operator and resolver. Latent until the repro write-back is wired, but must be fixed alongside it.|Gate writeReproducedBlock on a confirmed verdict: only render when f.Verification.Verdict==confirmed and f.EvidenceExec.ExitCode != 0, or make Stamp attach EvidenceExec only on a confirmed verdict. Add a render test feeding EvidenceExec with exit 0 / unverifiable and assert no badge.|correctness|30|internal/report/render.go:179-183|claude
MEDIUM|internal/report/render.go:377|writeReproducedBlock wraps the command in a backtick code span but feeds it through esc(), which HTML-escapes (< to &lt;) and rewrites backticks to &#96;. Inside a markdown code span those entities are not decoded, so any command containing < > & double-quote or single-quote renders as literal entity garbage. The package already has the correct codeSpan helper that escapes only when a backtick/newline is present; this function ignores it.|Render the command via the existing codeSpan logic (raw inside backticks for the common case, esc fallback only on backtick/CR/LF) instead of esc() inside a literal code span. Add a test with a command containing < and double-quote asserting the span is not entity-mangled.|maintainability|30|internal/report/render.go:376-381|claude
MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/emit.go:163|The non-cached branch of JSONFindings() rebuilds each JSONFinding from the library Merged value, which carries no EvidenceExec field, so the block is silently not copied. Unlike Verification (preserved by pointer) and FixWarning (documented as intentionally not copied), EvidenceExec has no comment and no carry — a reconcile round-trip through this derivation path destroys any evidence_exec with no trace, a latent data-loss trap for the field Epic 11.0 added.|Add an explanatory comment mirroring the FixWarning note that derivation-time producers never hold EvidenceExec, and if the cached path can ever be bypassed for a stamped finding, carry the field. Verify with a round-trip test.|maintainability|15|internal/reconcile/emit.go:162-184|claude
MEDIUM|internal/repro/repro.go:41|repro.Verdict returns confirmed whenever both runs share any equal non-zero exit code, carving out only TimedOut. A Docker OOM kill (137), exec/permission failure (126/127), or unrelated segfault (139) that reproduces across both runs is stamped confirmed — a this-finding-is-real claim with a failing command — even though the non-zero exit reflects infrastructure, not the asserted defect, defeating the determinism gate's purpose of resisting poisoned evidence.|Treat Docker-reserved infra codes (125/126/127/137 and the 128+n signal range) as unverifiable rather than confirmed in Verdict, or require the reproduction command to be the configured test command. Add table tests for exit 137/127 asserting unverifiable.|correctness|30|internal/repro/repro.go:34-45|claude
LOW|internal/sandbox/sandbox.go:105|The sandbox truncate helper appends the marker without reserving space for it, so the returned string is keep + len(marker) bytes — larger than limit — contradicting its doc (at most limit bytes); the dispatch.go truncate correctly subtracts the marker length. It also reports len(s)-limit bytes dropped while it actually cut at keep (<= limit), so the count is wrong when it backs off a multi-byte rune. MaxOutputBytes can be overshot on every truncated exec result.|Reserve marker length (keep = limit - len(marker), guard negative) and report len(s)-keep in the marker, mirroring dispatch.go truncate. Verify with a multibyte string at the boundary asserting len(result) <= limit.|maintainability|15|internal/sandbox/sandbox.go:105-115|claude
LOW|internal/tools/exec_tools.go:60|EnableExecution writes d.handlers/d.pathArgs/d.execBackend via mustRegister while Execute reads d.handlers from many parallel agent goroutines with no mutex. Safety rests on an unwritten called-once-during-construction ordering (only SetLimits carries that warning, not these fields); any wiring that calls EnableExecution after a goroutine has begun Execute is a concurrent map read+write — a fatal Go runtime error, not a benign race.|Document and assert the construction-before-concurrency contract at the EnableExecution call site, or guard registration/lookup with a sync.RWMutex (or build the handler map immutably before sharing). Verify with go test -race exercising EnableExecution concurrently with Execute.|maintainability|30|internal/tools/exec_tools.go:60-66|claude
LOW|internal/sandbox/docker.go:145|Run guards the concurrency semaphore with if b.sem != nil, and sem is allocated only in NewDockerBackend. A DockerBackend built as a struct literal (tests or future call sites) has a nil sem, so MaxConcurrent — described as the mitigation for the Critical-rated resource-abuse risk — is silently bypassed and unlimited containers can spawn. The fail-open default for the load-bearing cap is the wrong direction.|Lazily initialize the semaphore (or panic on nil sem) in Run, or make NewDockerBackend the only construction path. Verify with a test constructing the backend via struct literal and asserting the cap still applies.|security|15|internal/sandbox/docker.go:139-152|claude
LOW|internal/repro/repro.go:89|verdictRank hardcodes confirmed=3/unverifiable=2/refuted=1 and its own comment admits it mirrors internal/reconcile/merge.go precedence. merge.go owns the canonical ranking; two independent copies will silently desync if merge order changes, and Stamp's downgrade protection would then apply the wrong precedence.|Export the merge-package rank function (or a shared precedence constant set) and have Stamp call it instead of a private copy. Verify both call sites resolve to one symbol.|maintainability|30|internal/repro/repro.go:87-100|claude
LOW|cmd/atcr/review.go:149|In runReview, resolveExec (which runs registry.LoadProjectConfig plus a real container Preflight) is called before gitrange.Resolve and fanout.LoadReviewConfig, so an invalid git range or malformed review registry still pays the cost of spawning a preflight container, and the project config is parsed twice. The intent is fail-fast on --exec misconfig but it inverts cheap-checks-first ordering.|Move the resolveExec preflight after gitrange.Resolve and LoadReviewConfig succeed (still before any paid review API call), and thread the already-loaded project config into resolveExec to avoid the second parse. Verify a bad range errors without a container spawn.|performance|30|cmd/atcr/review.go:145-152|claude
